  <h1>Final Paycheck Deadlines by State</h1>
  <p>State law sets specific deadlines for when employers must issue a final paycheck after termination. Miss those deadlines and employers face statutory penalties that can dwarf the unpaid wages themselves. Below is a guide to notable states — from the most worker-favorable (California, Massachusetts) to the general rule in states with lighter penalty regimes.</p>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Morgan Kettering (MK), Editor-in-Chief &amp; Wage Theft Lead, SHRM-SCP. Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <h2>California — most worker-favorable</h2>
  <p>California has the strictest final-paycheck rules in the country, enforced by the Labor Commissioner's Office.</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Involuntary termination (fired, laid off):</strong> All wages due immediately at the time of termination. The employer must have the check ready when they hand you the notice.</li>
    <li><strong>Voluntary quit with 72+ hours advance notice:</strong> Final wages due on the last day of work.</li>
    <li><strong>Voluntary quit without 72 hours notice:</strong> Final wages due within 72 hours of the last day of work.</li>
    <li><strong>Penalty for late payment — "waiting time penalty" (Labor Code § 203):</strong> One full day's wages for each calendar day the final paycheck is late, capped at 30 days. This applies to involuntary terminations and is also available for voluntary quits in some circumstances. The penalty is calculated at the employee's regular daily rate of pay.</li>
  </ul>
  <p><strong>Example:</strong> A California employee earning $320/day is terminated and their employer takes 25 days to issue the final paycheck. Waiting-time penalty = $320 &times; 25 = $8,000, in addition to recovering the unpaid wages themselves.</p>
  <p>California also requires that employees be paid all accrued, unused vacation on termination — vacation time is treated as earned wages, and late or nonpayment triggers the same § 203 penalty.</p>

  <h2>Massachusetts — treble damages</h2>
  <p>Massachusetts imposes some of the most severe penalties for wage violations in the country, with mandatory multiplication of unpaid wages.</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Involuntary termination:</strong> Final wages due on the day of discharge.</li>
    <li><strong>Voluntary quit:</strong> Due on the next regular payday following the last day of work.</li>
    <li><strong>Penalty (M.G.L. c. 149, § 150):</strong> Treble (triple) damages on unpaid wages, plus mandatory attorney's fees. Courts have little discretion to reduce the trebling — it is statutory. This means a $5,000 unpaid final paycheck becomes a $15,000 exposure before fees.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Massachusetts enforcement is handled through the Attorney General's Fair Labor Division (free to file) or private litigation. The attorney's-fees provision makes employment attorneys especially willing to take these cases on contingency.</p>

  <h2>Illinois — 1% per day</h2>
  <p>Illinois uses a different penalty structure that grows over time.</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Final paycheck timing:</strong> Due on the next regular scheduled payday following the last day of employment.</li>
    <li><strong>Penalty (820 ILCS 115/14):</strong> 1% per day of the amount of underpayment or delay, plus attorney's fees. Unlike California's flat-day penalty, this accrues as a percentage, so it grows with both time and the size of the unpaid amount.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Example: $3,000 in unpaid final wages, 30 days late. Penalty = $3,000 &times; 1% &times; 30 = $900, plus attorney's fees. Illinois claims can be filed with the Illinois Department of Labor or through a private lawsuit.</p>

  <h2>New York — statutory damages plus fees</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Final paycheck timing:</strong> Due on the next regular payday after the last day of work.</li>
    <li><strong>Penalty (New York Labor Law § 198):</strong> Liquidated damages equal to 100% of underpaid wages, plus attorney's fees and costs, for willful violations. For non-willful violations, courts have discretion on liquidated damages. The New York Department of Labor also handles claims administratively at no cost to workers.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Texas — 6 days for involuntary termination</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Involuntary termination:</strong> Final wages due within 6 calendar days of discharge (Tex. Lab. Code § 61.014).</li>
    <li><strong>Voluntary quit:</strong> Due on the next regularly scheduled payday.</li>
    <li><strong>Penalty for willful violation:</strong> The lesser of treble damages or four weeks' wages, plus court costs. "Willful" requires more than simple delay — the employer must have known or shown reckless disregard for the obligation.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Texas wage claims can be filed with the Texas Workforce Commission.</p>

  <h2>Florida — no state deadline, FLSA applies</h2>
  <p>Florida does not have a specific state-level final-paycheck deadline. Employers must pay final wages on the next regular payday. Florida also has no state-level waiting-time penalty. Workers in Florida rely on the federal Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA), which requires timely payment of wages and allows recovery of unpaid wages, an equal amount in liquidated damages, plus attorney's fees for willful violations. Florida workers can file with the US Department of Labor's Wage and Hour Division or sue in federal court.</p>

  <h2>Washington — 3 days for involuntary termination</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Involuntary termination:</strong> Final wages due within 3 days (Rev. Code Wash. § 49.48.010).</li>
    <li><strong>Voluntary quit:</strong> Next regular payday or 3 days, whichever comes first.</li>
    <li><strong>Penalty:</strong> Double the wages withheld, plus attorney's fees (Rev. Code Wash. § 49.52.050) for willful withholding.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Colorado — immediate for involuntary, next payday for voluntary</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Involuntary termination:</strong> Final wages due immediately or within 6 hours of the next business day (Colo. Rev. Stat. § 8-4-109).</li>
    <li><strong>Voluntary quit:</strong> Next regular payday, or within 14 days, whichever is earlier.</li>
    <li><strong>Penalty:</strong> 50% of underpaid wages for willful withholding, with additional penalties possible through CDLE administrative process.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>States with next-payday rules and lower penalties</h2>
  <p>Most states require final paychecks on the next regular payday following termination — both for involuntary and voluntary separations. Penalties in these states are typically lower than California and Massachusetts, but unpaid wages remain recoverable. Common remedies include actual unpaid wages plus interest, statutory damages of 25–100% of the unpaid amount, and attorney's fees in some states. States in this general category include Georgia, Ohio, Pennsylvania, Michigan, Arizona, and many others.</p>
  <p>Even in states with lighter penalty regimes, unpaid wages are recoverable through the state labor agency or private lawsuit. Filing with the labor agency is typically free, doesn't require a lawyer, and pauses any statute-of-limitations clock during the administrative process.</p>

  <h2>Federal baseline (FLSA)</h2>
  <p>The federal Fair Labor Standards Act sets a floor across all states: employers must pay wages on the established payday. For willful violations, workers can recover: (1) unpaid wages, (2) an equal amount in liquidated damages, and (3) attorney's fees. The FLSA has a 2-year statute of limitations (3 years for willful violations). State remedies are generally more favorable than federal remedies for final-paycheck claims, so most attorneys file state claims rather than federal ones.</p>

  <h2>What to do if your final paycheck is late</h2>
  <p>Step one: send a written demand to your former employer's HR or payroll department, referencing the applicable statute and the amount owed. Step two: file with your state labor agency — free to file, no attorney required. Step three: if the amount is significant or the employer refuses to pay, consult an employment attorney. Most wage-theft attorneys work on contingency for these cases. See our full guide: <a href="/guides/what-to-do-if-paid-late">What to do if you're paid late</a>.</p>

  <p>Use our <a href="/">calculator</a> to estimate the California waiting-time penalty or other late-paycheck amounts before you start the process.</p>
